description:
Vespula germanica (Fabricius, 1793) è una specie di imenottero Apocrita della famiglia delle Vespidae.

La Vespula germanica è originaria dell'Europa sebbene sia riuscita ormai ad acclimatarsi bene anche nel continente americano. È presente anche in Nuova Zelanda.

In primavera la regina svernante comincia a costruire un primo mucchietto di cellette; queste sono prodotte con schegge di legno secco o frammenti di cartone impastati con la saliva della vespa che vanno a formare una pasta modellabile. Il materiale appena modellato si indurisce e prende una consistenza cartacea. Le prime cellette sono coperte da un involucro delle dimensioni di una noce, sempre cartaceo ma questa volta impermeabile, che ripara il primo gruppo di celle nelle quali si sviluppano le prime operaie della nuova colonia. La regina, finché non nascono le operaie, si occuperà di ampliare il nido, difenderlo e ripararlo se rovinato, nonché di procurare il nutrimento per le larve: tutti compiti che spetteranno alle vespe operaie una volta nate; a quel punto alla regina non resterà che deporre le uova e assicurarsi che tutte le larve e le operaie siano esclusivamente sue figlie, uccidendo o cacciando eventuali intruse. Il nido quindi viene ampliato dalle operaie nascenti, aggiungendo sempre più strati attorno alla copertura iniziale che viene quindi demolita, per far aumentare il numero di cellette. Presto un solo piano di cellette non basta più e subito ne vengono costruiti altri paralleli al piano iniziale, collegati fra loro con appositi pilastri cartacei. In poco tempo il nido raggiunge le dimensioni di un panettone.

Mentre il nido aumenta di dimensione, la regina ha sempre più cellette a disposizione per deporre le uova; per tutta la durata dell'estate il nido continua ad ampliarsi e le operaie continuano ad aumentare di numero. Le ultime covate di operaie, essendo più nutrite, producono operaie grandi quanto regine e difficili nella distinzione da queste ultime. Una volta nate le ultime operaie è ormai autunno inoltrato e ci sono già migliaia di esemplari: allora la regina cessa provvisoriamente di deporre le uova per lasciare sufficiente spazio alla covata successiva. L'ultima covata, prima della morte della regina, genererà nuove regine ed esemplari maschi: è quasi inverno. Le operaie stanno ormai morendo e ne restano sempre meno dopo la morte della regina ormai troppo anziana. Le poche operaie rimaste si dedicano esclusivamente al nutrimento e alla difesa delle nuove femmine fertili e dei maschi per prepararli al volo nuziale che solitamente si svolge quando le temperature sono ormai basse. Le giovani regine ed i maschi, quindi, volano via dal nido di appartenenza e si disperdono assieme ad altri sessuati di altri nidi. Quando una femmina fertile incontra un maschio, non necessariamente proveniente da un diverso nido, ha luogo l'accoppiamento, dopo il quale il maschio muore e la femmina fecondata va a svernare nel legno marcio o sotto terra, in attesa della bella stagione per riavviare il ciclo vitale.

description:
Splat!


This bugger landed on the table, so I did what any conservationist would have done - I squashed it with my book and continued sipping my wine! One less problem in the world.
Searched the area but couldn't locate any nests, but saw many collecting nesting material from the bamboo shade material above the tables outside the conference hall.

I have only seen this amazing looking wasp twice - once a week or two ago, and then today. Initially I thought it was actually two insects having, you know, “intimate relations” in the air, but no, it is just one, giant, wasp. 

I saw it three times today in the same areas - it only went to certain parts of the garden - and it seemed to be looking for something, similar to the behaviour of the Red spider hunting wasp (Pompilidae), and it had constantly twitching antenna like the Lemon Tree Borer Parasite - which it also resembles. 

It was hard to photograph was it seldom settled down, and when it did it either wasn’t there for long or it was crawling around under leaves, and I’m hoping over plants and around bushes trying to get to it before it flies away. 

It does look very like the Whitespotted Ichneumonid (Ecthromorpha intracatoria) seen here https://www.landcareresearch.co.nz/resources/identification/animals/bug-id/what-is-this-bug/bugs-with-legs/6-legs/bees-and-wasps/whitespotted-ichneumonid but they list the size as 15mm and this was definitely over 2.5cm, I’d say 28mm but I couldn’t really get a good check on it as it kept flying around. It’s also missing the second dark patch shown on the wings, but I think the end of it’s wings might be shredded at the ends and a lot shorter than they’re supposed to be. 

I also got to see it get briefly attacked by either a common or german wasp while they were both checking out the same plant, but it shook it off and the other wasp obviously wasn’t that interested.

description: On a piece of fire wood.  Stung me.

Wasp - Batozonellus vespoides Identified as Batozonellus vespoides on Bowerbird by Ken Walker: "This identification took some getting!! First, as Jenny suggested it looked like an ichneumonid wasp but with only 13 antennal segments it could not be such. Eventually, I sent out a query to the Australian entomological community asking for help. Dr John LaSalle suggested it may be a pompilid and forwarded my email to a German colleague who is currently revising the Australian pompilid. Lars Krogmann returned an identification within the same day I sent my original call for help. What a great network and what a great find. Here is what Lar said about this species: "The species is Batozonellus vespoides Smith, 1868 in the subfamily Pompilinae. The species seems to be relatively common along the Northeastern, Eastern and Southeastern coast of Australia with state records from QLD, VIC, ACT and SA." Of course yet again, Jenny record will provide ALA with the first location and image for this species."

cm: 20.5 g M > F . M (br) A small weaver with white or pale yellow eyes and grey legs. The black mask extends to the centre of the crown. The lower edge of the black bib on the throat is rounded (not pointed) as in Southern Masked Weaver. M (non-br) Lacks black face mask and has duller plumage; bill dark horn coloured, and legs blue-grey (not pinkish brown as in Southern Masked Weaver and Village Weaver. F. Less yellow below than non-br M ; eyes whitish yellow. Belly becomes whitish in the non-br season. Juv. Resembles non-br F .
Status Locally common resident, gregarious and nomadic in the non-breeding season.
Habitat Savanna woodland, especially thornveld; usually not far from water.
Food Insects, seeds & nectar.
Call Typical rasping weaver swizzles.
BreedingPolygynous and colonial. Usually nests in trees (often over water), sometimes in reedbeds. Nest has distinctive short, very narrow entrance tunnel. Occasional host to Diderick Cuckoo.

SOUNDS

Song from individuals in a colony January, Kruger NP. G. Gibbon.
ROBERTS VII TEXT

Lesser Masked Weaver
Ploceus intermedius

Ploceus intermedius Rüppell, 1845, Syst. Uebers, pp71, 76; Shoa, c Ethiopia. intermedius (L) = intermediate in size.

IDENTIFICATION: 14-15 cm, ca 20 g. Sexes dimorphic in br plumage coloration. (P. i. cabanisii)
Ad male br: Forehead to mid-crown, and face and throat black, latter ending in rounded bib on foreneck. Hind crown and nape yellow, with slight golden-brown wash around mask. Remainder of upper parts yellowish green, mantle, back and lesser wing coverts streaked dark grey-olive; rump and upper tail coverts plain. Tail dark olive-grey, edged yellowish green. Flight feathers and primary coverts dark grey-brown, edged greenish yellow; tertials, and greater and median coverts broadly edged greenish yellow. Underwing pale yellowish white. Upper breast to vent bright yellow. Bill black. Eyes whitish yellow. Legs and feet blue-grey.
Ad male non-br: As br male, but lacks black face mask. Upper parts duller, with olive of back extending onto crown. Faint yellowish supercilium contrasts weakly with olive-washed lores, cheeks and ear coverts. Throat pale yellow-olive; remainder of underparts yellow, breast washed brown, flanks washed olive. Bill dark horn, base pinkish. Occurrence of this plumage in s Africa uncertain (see Moult).
Ad female br: As non-br male, but duller, underparts less yellow.
Ad female non-br: As br female, but belly whitish.
Juv: As non-br female.
Confusing species: Breeding male Southern Masked- Weaver and Village Weaver have red (not whitish-yellow) eyes and pinkish-brown (not blue-grey) legs. Pale eye separates ad female and juv from all except Spectacled and Holub's Golden Weavers. Former has black loral stripe (both sexes) and latter has heavy, black conical bill and uniform yellow mantle. Male Cape Weaver also has a pale eye, but is much larger, with an obviously long and large bill.

VOICE: Song typical weaver rasping swizzles; rather liquid chatter, sometimes with hollow, gobbling quality. Call notes incl tyewp, pew-pew-pew and tsop-tsop.

DISTRIBUTION: Eastern and s Africa from n Somalia, Ethiopia and s Sudan south through Zambia and e DRC to s Africa; locally along coastal plain of Congo and Angola. In s Africa, in n Namibia (patchy), n and se Botswana, Zimbabwe (except broad-leaved woodland in west, and eastern highlands), and locally in Mozambique and lowveld of Swaziland. In S Africa, locally common in Limpopo Province, Mpumalanga, NW Province adjacent to Botswana border, and n KwaZulu-Natal.

POPULATION & DEMOGRAPHY: Locally common. In s Mozambique, est > 2 000 birds, Swaziland 600, Kruger NP, S Africa 130 000 ads. Ringing records suggest male:female sex ratio of 1.44:1 (n = 2 142). Longevity of ringed birds at least 9 yr. Ad killed by Gabar Goshawk; 1 strangled by fishing line used in nest construction. Of 14 ringed birds found dead, 6 trapped for food, 1 shot and 1 collided with window. Blood parasites incl Haemoproteus and Leucocytozoon spp.

MOVEMENTS: Resident, sedentary and local nomad; colonies deserted in non-br season. Brief showers cause start of nest building, but if no follow-up rain, birds disperse. In Botswana, apparently disappears in some years. Furthest movement of ringed bird 74 km in Limpopo Province (n = 14 recoveries, 31 recaptures).

HABITAT: Acacia savanna, bushveld, open woodland, riverine trees, swamps, reedbeds and mangroves, preferring areas close to water; often nests close to human habitation.

GENERAL HABITS: Gregarious in small flocks or solitary when not br. In Botswana, joins large flocks of other weavers in winter and roosts with other ploceids, incl Red-billed Quelea.

FORAGING & FOOD: Forages in tree canopies (especially Umbrella Thorn Acacia tortilis and Ana-tree Faidherbia albida) for insects, probing under leaves. Probes flowers for insects and nectar, face may become stained orange or yellow with pollen. Eats insects, especially caterpillars; also termites and grasshoppers. Also takes nectar (mainly of Aloe spp), flowers of Albizia spp, mulberries (Morus spp), small seeds, and maize porridge in gardens.

BREEDING: Polygynous, br in colonies with several males and 10-30 nests, sometimes up to 200 nests. 1 male may have 2-3 female simultaneously, and probably several more in a season. Male displays from nest by rapidly fanning wings, spreading tail, and swaying head slightly while singing.
Nest: Built by male. Kidney-shaped, thin-walled but strong, with downward-pointing entrance tunnel. Built of narrow strips of grass, reed or palm leaves and fine, fresh, green grass heads; 1 built of pine (Pinus sp) needles. Short lengths of material protrude from nest, giving it an untidy look. Female lines accepted nests, but often with little material (silky grey fibres, sometimes a few grass heads); br nest sometimes not lined. Front to back 130-140 mm, height 80-95 mm; entrance tunnel length 25-120 mm, diam 30-35 mm (n = 10). Placed at end of branch on outside or inside of tree, or in bush, often over water. Nest trees incl Fever-tree Acacia Acacia xanthophloea, other Acacia spp, figs (Ficus spp), mangroves, Flamboyant Delonix regia, pepper-trees (Schinus spp), Persian Lilac Melia azaderach, palms (Borassus spp) and Eucalyptus spp. Also in reeds (Phragmites spp), Bulrushes Typha capensis, Papyrus Cyperus papyrus and bamboos (Bambusidae), or hung from edge of roof or from telephone wire. Nests usually very close together, sometimes suspended from other nests. Sometimes nests close to paper wasps' nests (Vespidae). Colonies may be mixed with other weavers, especially Village Weaver; also Southern Masked- Weaver, Eastern Holub's Golden Weaver, and Thick-billed Weaver, and Red-billed Quelea.
Laying dates: Botswana Oct-Feb (n = 17); Zimbabwe Aug-Mar (187 of 219 records Oct-Jan); S Africa Oct-Feb, peak Dec (n = 55).
Eggs: 2-4 (2.4, n = 150). Oval to elongated oval. White or pale bluish white, unmarked, with little or no gloss; coarse-grained, with obvious pores. Size (n = 74) 18.5-23.5 x 13.9-15.6 mm (21.4 x 14.7 mm).
Incubation: Period 13 d, by female only; 48% of day spent incubating.
Development & care of young: Young brooded by female; fed mostly by female, on insects, incl caterpillars. Nestling period 15-16 d.
Breeding success: Occasional host to Diderick Cuckoo (2.4% of nests parasitized in s Africa, 6% in Zambia)and very rarely Klaas's Cuckoo. Eggs and nestlings taken by snakes, particularly Boomslang Dispholidus typus, also by African Fish- Eagle and Vervet Monkey Cercopithecus aethiops.

CONSERVATION: Not threatened.

MOULT: Ads have complete post-br moult; active primary moult recorded Nov (n = 4) and Jan-May (n = 30). In e Africa, male has eclipse plumage with associated pre-br moult, this not confirmed in s Africa or DRC. Low reporting rates Apr-Jul suggest males in non-br plumage, but could also be explained by movement.

GEOGRAPHICAL VARIATION: Mainly in extent and shades of chestnut wash on breast and flanks, and shade of yellow on hind crown and breast. Subspp: Africa 3, s Africa 1.
1. P. i. cabanisii Peters, 1868, J. Ornithol., 16:133; Inhambane, Mozambique (incl P. i. luebberti Reichenow). Throughout the species' range in s Africa; extralimitally, north to coastal Tanzania; also in interior of s Angola, where range disjunct from P. i. beattyi to the north. (Described under Identification.)

MEASUREMENTS: P. i. cabanisii wing (140 male) 67-78 (72.8), (112 female) 65-78 (69.6); tail (29 unsexed) 46-56 (no mean); tarsus (29 unsexed) 18-22 (no mean); culmen (29 unsexed) 14-17 (no mean); mass (777 male) 15.0-43.0 (21.4), (499 female) 15.0-32.9 (19.8).

description:
Temperature (f): 77 degrees
Weather Conditions: Hot, no wind, calm, felt like summer again

Today was the most exciting day of observations so far. It is the first day that I’ve seen flowers on the green bush on the right side of my site (Chinese holly). In addition to that, I witnessed a new pollinator visit the site: The Coarse-backed Red Paper Wasp. There was also a great deal of activity within my site, including 5 or 6 German Yellowjackets, a couple small flies, some gnats, and 2 Coarse-backed Red Paper Wasps. I think this increase in activity can be attributed to the blooming of flowers on the Chinese Holly plant.

Temperature (f): 73 degrees
Weather Conditions: cool, borderline chilly, sun-setting


Similar to my observations on 9-21-2020, there were very few pollinators at my site. I spotted 2 German yellowjackets and 1 Coarse-backed Red Paper Wasp; all of them seemed uneasy. This observation leads me to believe that as we move further into fall, and thus the sun sets earlier, the insects that interact with my site may become less active earlier in the evening. This is possibly why I am not seeing as many pollinators when I make observations later in the day as opposed to in the morning or afternoon.

description:
Excavating the nest: Yellow jacket emerges from center of nest with a cement clump to carry away, the next yellow jacket (next photo), identifying alternating bands on its abdomen, arrives on the left to re-enter the nest; by midsummer, the first adult workers emerge and assume the tasks of nest expansion, foraging for food, care of the queen and larvae, and colony defense, and from this time until her death in the autumn, the queen remains inside the nest, laying eggs (the colony expands rapidly, to 4000-5000 workers and a nest of 10,000-15,000 cells in late summer), success of these wasps is due in part to their high cognitive plasticity, important learning and memory capacities enabling them to memorize various resource characteristics, including the route to resources, as well as specific spatial location with respect to local landmarks, and sensorimotor learning capacities allowing them to associate visual stimuli with certain motor responses.

The predatory social German wasp, their mouthparts with well-developed with strong mandibles, has typical black and yellow colors very similar to the common wasp (V. vulgaris), but with 3 tiny black dots on the clypeus; they are identified by their distinctive markings, occurrence only in colonies, and a characteristic rapid side-to-side flight pattern prior to landing, and sometimes mistakenly called "bees", in that they are similar in size and sting, but yellowjackets are actually wasps.
